iginal perspectives and allows students to develop their own understanding of what it means to be Aboriginal and what it means to be Canadian.',0),(2910,98,'1000','INsight: Essentials for a Successful University Experience',0,'Insight is a non-credit course that takes place over both the fall and winter terms. The course will provide clear learning strategies to support academic success. Students will attend lectures and learning skills workshops, explore related readings, keep a journal and work with a mentor. The program is comprised of 19 two hour weekly lectures/workshops and ongoing mentoring support. Note (1): This course will not count for academic credit. Note (2): This course is not open to all students; enrolment is restricted. Course credit exclusions: None',0),(2911,98,'4000','Individualized Studies Thesis',6,'The purpose of this course is to offer individualized studies students a change to draw together the parts of their topic by carrying out a sustained piece of research and writing. An adviser, arranged for by the student, directs the thesis and acts as one of its reader. Normally the finished thesis is around 60 pages in length. Note: All who intend to register in AP/INDV 4000 6.00 must submit a thesis proposal to the coordinator by September 30. Course credit exclusions: None. Prior TO FALL 2009: Course credit exclusion:AS/INDV 4000 6.00.',0),(2912,99,'5000','Interdisciplinary Seminar',6,'Interdisciplinary Seminar. Discussion conducted by the Candidate\'s Supervisory Committee, focussing on the Candidate\'s thesis area and designed to integrate the knowledge gained in courses taken under other graduate programmes. Required of all Candidates.',0),(2913,99,'5010','Directed Readings',3,'Directed Reading',0),(2914,99,'5020','Directed Readings',6,'Directed Reading',0),(2915,99,'5030','Practicum',6,'Practicum. The acquisition of specialized skills, the mastery of mechanical techniques or of the principles of a particular discipline; and supervised exper