ation than non-lawyers? What are the indicia of good regulation? To what extent are regulatory norms or practices influenced by broader social, political or economic developments, such as globalization, neo-liberalism, or technological determinism? What are the tools of regulatory intervention? Is the distinction between social and economic regulation a viable one? How does the idea of governance differ from the idea of regulation? What are the new institutions of governance in the 21st century? Is there something unique about the phenomenon of risk regulation? What is the role of citizen engagement in regulatory activity?',0),(3214,114,'6136','Study Group on Regulation and Governance II',0,'The scholarship canvassed in this study group will address a broad set of questions concerning the role of regulation and governance in ordering social, economic and political life. One of the exciting things about the subject matter is that it is intensely debated by a broad range of scholars operating from a variety of perspectives, such as lawyers, sociologists, political scientists, economists, geographers, and legal and political philosophers. A range of fundamental questions may be recurring themes as we discuss our material. Such questions include; what exactly do we mean by regulation? Is it a coherent concept? Does it necessarily involve the state acting in some directive capacity? Is a regulatory agency required? What produces regulatory change? Do lawyers have a different understanding of regulation than non-lawyers? What are the indicia of good regulation? To what extent are regulatory norms or practices influenced by broader social, political or economic developments, such as globalization, neo-liberalism, or technological determinism? What are the tools of regulatory intervention? Is the distinction between social and economic regulation a viable one? How does the idea of governance differ from the idea of regulation? What are the new institutions of governance in 